04826nam a22006615i 9781487579821DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20201980onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875798217 a10.3138/97814875798212doi  a(DE-B1597)549343  a(OCoLC)1153484687  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aHIS0250002bisacsh04a301.44/43/097241 aSchryer, Frans J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Rancheros of Pisaflores :bThe History of a Peasant Bourgeoisie in Twentieth-Century Mexico /cFrans J. Schryer. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©1980  a1 online resource (228 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Introduction -- tPART ONE. LAND TENURE AND POLITICS IN THE SIERRA ALTA -- t2. The History of a Ranchero Economy -- t3. Village Politics and Class Structure: An Analysis -- tPART TWO. PISAFLORES: A CASE STUDY OF AGRARIAN POLITICS -- t4. Landowners as 'Revolutionaries' 1910-32 -- t5. Agrarianism as Politics 1932-44 -- t6. PRI Patronage and Factional Politics 1945-6o -- t7. Middle Peasants in the Struggle for Land -- t8. A Case Study of Co-optation 1960-76 -- t9. Conclusion -- tEpilogue -- tAppendix: The Most Important Documents Found in the Archives of Jacala and Pisaflores -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis case study of the 'ranchero' region of Sierra Alta de Hidalgo offers a new perspective on the rancheros and their role in the Mexican Revolution and its aftermath. Focusing on the economic and political history of the municipio of Pisaflores over the past hundred years, the author demonstrates that the rancheros were not subsistence family farmers, as they have been described by other scholars, but commercial farmers, a local elite employing wage labourers. This 'peasant bourgeoisie' far outnumbered the absentee owners of a huge hacienda who figure so prominently in the literature, and they played an important part in the armed phase of the Mexican Revolution that started in 1910. The Revolution, in fact, provided individual members of this rural class with a unique opportunity to improve their economic and social position. In the Sierra Alta de Hidalgo many rancheros became local revolutionaries, recruiting their own employees and tenants, and two members of prominent ranchero families eventually became governors of central states. A detailed political history of Pisaflores between 1920 and 1970 shows how the rancheros responded to the larger economic changes in twentieth-century Mexico. The author suggests that the political behaviour of the peasant bourgeoisie was a logical outcome of the pattern of land tenure and its corresponding class structure. The book as a whole provides new insights into the operation of the de facto one-party system of Mexico, the use of an agrarian ideology, the operation of land reform, and the changing network of links between local, regional, and national politicians in this remote but not insignificant rural region.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPeasantszMexicozPisaflores, region (Veracruz)xHistory. 0aPolitical participationzMexicozPisaflores, region (Veracruz)xHistory. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148757982140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487579821423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487579821.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  a